narratives.question_text: What were the strengths and weaknesses of your teaching assistant
comments: Instructor: Daniel Maynard  Leanne was very helpful and accessible, and committed a substantial amount of time to helping students outside of class. Her help was essential for my success in this course.

Instructor: Daniel Maynard  She was very good at giving equal time to all the students waiting for her assistance. I don't think she ever once cancelled her office hours, which seemed to be a common occurrence for other TAs and was very difficult on people who depended on them. She was great at explaining concepts that weren't clear in class.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Very approachable and provides excellent guidance
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Leanne was great! Sometimes looking over the homework before we come with questions would be useful, but this is a small request.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Strengths - was able to explain problem in simpler manner Weakness - if he could mention the better option of answering the questions in the problem sets
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Fjodor was not accessible
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  he graded homeworks in a timely manner!

Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Fjodor was frequently absent during his schedule hours, and provided only brief advance notice regarding these absences. In my limited interactions with him, he rarely showed interest in advancing student understanding of the material, and was not particularly adept at clarifying questions.

Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  He was never prepared for his office hours. He never looked at the homework until we showed him a question. After a while I stopped asking for help because it would take so long for him to read the question, understand the point, understand my question, and then provide an answer...

Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  As indicated above, I worked with Leanne Weiss more closely than Fjodor or Dan. Leanne was patient, and always willing to go out of her way to explain difficult concepts in a way that was clear. I really appreciate her help this semester; she is a very patient tutor. I went to tutoring with Fjodor several times, and he was also helpful but significantly less engaging than Leanne. I never went to tutoring with Dan, so I cannot comment on his effectiveness.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Always willing to help and helpful at explaining hard-to-understand concepts!
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  I did not use the assistance of any Teaching Fellow for this course.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  My teaching assistant did not make himself very available to us. He was always unprepared for TA sessions.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  Great TA. Helpful comments on homeworks.
Instructor: Fjodor Melnikov  The teaching assistant was very helpful and enthusiastic however did not always have knowledge of the software we were using in class.

narratives.question_text: Use the space below to comment on questions 1-14, if you wish
comments: I was lost once we hit transformations/logs/etc., but overall felt the course was extremely helpful. The material is covered quickly and I found it difficult to keep up with the concepts, but the homework wasn't overly burdensome. I greatly appreciated the statistical concepts that I'll take away for the course even if I will always feel more comfortable calling a statistician than doing the stats myself!

I honestly couldn't think of a way for Jonathan to be a better teacher. I was really not looking forward to taking a stats class, but Jonathan made this class so entertaining and engaging, and was able to explain everything in a way that students understood it. Great job!

Dr. Reuning Scherer was a difficult teacher to follow in the classroom. He moved very quickly, and did not maintain a good balance between the tasks of advancing student understanding of the basic principles of statistics and equipping us to interpret outside expert analyses. I attribute some of this apparent ineptitude to the murky goals of the course at large, because Dr. Reuning Scherer was helpful and clearly committed to student learning outside of the classroom.
It is essential to be familiar with statistical concepts and this was a great introduction course that focused more on applied statistics rather than the mathematics behind it.

Jonathan has a tough job here! I'm sure it's not easy to teach statistics to a group of non-math majors, but he did a very good job of making the course engaging through the use of real world examples. Jonathan's humor also goes a long way in making the class engaging, which is something that I very much appreciate. I think Intro to Stats should be a requirement for all master's students. I took Intro to Environmental Science during my undergrad, but I still learned a great deal through this course.
Question 4: Sometimes the way of professor on explaining the subject slightly on a high speed.

The course would be improved by explaining when to use each type of statistical analysis. (This happens to some degree with the "Incomplete Guide" during the last week.) I recommend summarizing when and how different analyses are used. Class slides are cluttered and not useful for reviewing key concepts. If possible, make them cleaner and explicitly state which topic is being addressed.

narratives.question_text: What were the best aspects of this course?
comments: Very engaging professor
Very animated mode of teaching and making the course more application oriented
Working through data analysis in class (more towards the end of the class) Final project Professor Reuning-Scherer helping us work through our final project data, more lab style was great
- The professor
The videos were quite helpful when you didn't understand from the slides, a great source of guide.
The lectures were engaging
Jonathan is amazing teacher, just go to his office hours and ask any questions you have. he won't make you feel dumb, and is patience is out of this world for helping people with stats.
The final project was a useful exercise.
Great balance of homeworks, take-home tests, and project. It puts less pressure on the grade and more on actually learning the material.

The homework! Strange response, I know, but the homework was really important for me in helping to solidify difficult concepts. Tutoring was also key. I have no clue how or why anyone goes through this class without ever attending tutoring.

Assignments were helpful in reviewing materials, and the instructor really does try his best to keep students engaged with what could be dry material. Concrete examples and demonstrations were very helpful.

The course follows the 'learn by doing' which i like the most. the concepts and examples are explained in the class as well as in the video lectures and you practically review your understanding by solving the problem sets.
The Professor was really fun. I like him
Helpful problem sets, funny instructor, good for understanding basic statistics.
Clear lectures, hands-on assistance with homework in the flipped course.

Professor Reuning-Scherer led an excellent class. He was energetic at every class meeting, patient with student questions, and found ways to make the material interesting. This is my third college or graduate level statistics class, and the teaching ability of Prof. Reuning-Scherer far exceeds tenured lecturers at Middlebury and Harvard. He was especially useful in a one-on-one or small group setting, and worked very hard to make himself available. He is the most accessible professor I know at Yale.
learning the use of Minitab as well as the different statistical analysis methods
the problem sets, which really helped us to work out the material
The final project and in-class interactive problem solving day were the best.

narratives.question_text: What aspects of this course need the most improvement?
comments: It was nearly impossible for me to attend the TA help sessions every time conflicted with another course I had this semester.
The pace was too fast. Other than that, this is an excellent course.
Nothing

I know that there are students with a range of learning styles and it's difficult to cater to everyone. That said, I would have benefitted from having a text book that the course was explicitly linked to. I did get a textbook for this course, but because the course followed a different outline it was difficult to know what to read beforehand (which I really need to do to understand fully what is going on in class). During the beginning of the course, sometimes it felt that there was not any space made for checking student comprehension or for questions. This improved later in the course though.
- The notes can be more organized better :)
Jonathan needs to speak slower and he goes really fast. Its difficult especially for International students.
Better preparation for final project
Honestly, I thought some of the homework and tests were too easy.

the lecture notes are all over the place. I'd love to have the diagram you gave at the end of the semester on which test you use and when, couple that with a chart of the different formulas for sd, variance, mean, etc + minitab + other stats formulas to use them. It was quite hard to try and go back and decipher the lecture notes to find the specific formulas. (the lectures were great, but my notetaking was lackadaisical i guess). provide specific problem sets to students beyond the homework for extra practice. it was a lot of work to try and find useful ones in the various book options.

Lecture could be much improved, either by gearing it more heavily towards teaching the fundamental mathematics behind statistics, or towards interpreting expert analyses. Presently, it is a hodgepodge that does not adequately serve either purpose.
Sometimes it was hard to follow along with the textbook due to the speed of the class. I would read along but then we would move quickly in class - maybe an updated syllabus as the weeks go by.

That's a tough question. Jonathan does a great job with this course, and Statistics is meant to be at least somewhat challenging. I struggled most during the probability section of the course, but I don't necessarily think we should have slowed down there more than we already did.

The course was very fast-paced, with lots of information packed pretty tightly. I do feel that it was all well-presented, and the homework assignments helped for reviewing important concepts, but I do feel as though I will have to re-learn a lot of the material later in order to really have a grasp of what I'm doing.
I would appreciate if professor slows down a bit when he speaks.
It would be great if the professor would go a bit slower when he speaks.
If the Professor would consider the variability of background, including those who are non-native language, I think the course would easy to understand.
A little too fast at times.
Non-flipped should have more CSSSI sessions for help with homework.

Probability is hard, and I had to teach myself using a textbook (OpenIntro Stats) and an "Idiot's Guide to Stats" book. I suggestion more carefully recommending self-teaching materials, especially for probability.
The speed of the class was too fast hence missing some critical details. I was left behind as I could not keep up at some point
Wouldn't change anything.
It covers too much material in too little time.

narratives.question_text: Discuss, if you wish, how this course fits into your overall program.  (Please feel free to describe how the course relates to your academic background.)
comments: I found it helpful
I am interested in quantitative methods and this was just the right introduction
Will help with analyzing research
I am a researcher, and will undoubtedly be using stats in the future. This was an excellent start to my stats journey...
good intro, hoping to take more stats classes
This course was of very limited utility. I intended it as a refresher in statistics, but found that it did not add meaningfully to my understanding of the field from undergraduate coursework.

I think Statistics should be a required course for all students at the School of Forestry. MESc candidates need a firm grasp of statistics for their own data analysis, and MEM candidates need a deep understanding of statistics to better analyze research that they may use to make environmental policies. I think a huge issue with the environmental movement right now is that very few environmental advocates feel comfortable speaking quantitatively, which is something that other interest groups (such as the coal or nuclear power industry, for instance), can do very confidently and convincingly.

Though not required by my specific program, statistical skills will be invaluable for me in conducting research both as a student and potentially in the workplace. I had only a single statistical course as an undergrad, and felt that I really needed to develop this skill set in order for me to be capable of completing my program here.
Statistics is a skill that is required by all managers.
it really fits my overall program on environmental science. I have taken stats courses before, and this course helped to better understand how to use stat tools in different environmental issues
As a joint law student, stats comes up often and knowing how stats works provides a deeper understanding of what I'll be working with.
Great instruction, highly recommended for math-inclined, and non-inclined, folks alike.
Understanding data is a major part of policy and effective decision making. This course is important to my specialization and my work in policy
This course will help me to analyze my own research.

narratives.question_text: If yes, what were the advantages and disadvantages of the group work?
comments: It's helpful to teach and be taught by peers; go at your own speed
It was not required (which I appreciated), but allowed us to explore data that would have been too much work to pull together as only one person.
for the final project we are working as a team and i find it effective as we are less stressed as the work load is divided. We are able to help each other and gets things done faster.
This was the most useful learning experience associated with the class.

I worked in a group with two other students to complete our final project, and it was great! Group work gives everyone a chance to play towards their strengths, and it also gave us the opportunity to discuss our data and bounce ideas back and forth. I have worked in groups where some people slacked off, but that didn't happen at all with this group. As Jonathan said might be the case, the final project was one of my favorite parts of this class.
Advantages I learned a lot about the course from my group friends Could solve the problem sets easily with many ideas in the group. I got a chance to make more friends.
Advantages Share knowledge Solve the problem set or project quick and learn as well Get to know more people.
I did the final project with two other persons and that was really helpful in term of sharing the burden and also improving my understanding to the materials
Same as any group work--working with a group is more fun and probably yields a better project, but harder to organize and spread out the work.
Critical for homework assignments.
Group work helped me finish up my assignments and project. it also gave me a better understanding of the some section I did not understand in class
More fun, very useful.

narratives.question_text: For students who might consider taking this course, what advice would you give them?
comments: Do it!
I think this would be a good one off course if you don't plan to take more statistical coursework, but if you do maybe look for something a bit more focused?
- Go to Jonathan's office hour - Get the Cartoon Guide
Not to miss the class as things gets messed even if you miss a class

Go to every lecture and stay focused. If you drift off for a minute, you can get lost. Also, don't worry about doing the textbook readings before class. I only read the textbook after lecture if there was something that I was still confused about.
if you're ever going to take stats, take this course with jonathan. go to office hours early and often, lose any inhibitions about asking dumb questions. Try and get extra problem sets for practice.
This course is un-necessary if you have any prior background in statistics.

Get one of the textbooks. The class moves quickly and it is easy to be "inactive" during class since the notes are provided for you. However, being "inactive" is not conducive to doing the homeworks, which really test your understanding, therefore get the textbook so you can be prepared for each class so it is more meaningful.
Take it. I guarantee this class will make you feel more confident when you assess the validity of research papers, and it will certainly be needed if you plan to conduct your own research.
Seek help early!
Always try to keep up with the class and never procastinate.
Submit the assignments and home works on time, Never miss classes.
You should take this course, no matter what background do you have. It easy to understand and the professor also supplied us with the video in case you missed something in the class session.
Take it! Borrow a book from the library as a reference, as there's no assigned textbook.
Take it! Read the Cartoon Guide, and visit JDRS often and early to clarify lectures and get help on coursework.
Take the class, even if you've hated statistics in the past!
Data is increasing becoming a crucial tool in decision making and understanding its analysis could not be more valuable
Great class, great & engaging lecturer, not a lot of work, learned a lot
